<div id="review_2662569590" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2662569590" />
    <a title="Krista Claudine Baetiong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong"><img alt="Krista Claudine Baetiong" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1552474554p2/13624574.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2662569590?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Krista Claudine Baetiong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Krista Claudine Baetiong" href="/user/show/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong">Krista Claudine Baetiong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=period-medieval">period-medieval</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=author-asia">author-asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13624574-krista-claudine-baetiong?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2662569590" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3413163298874159521">How can love endure without a touch of one’s hand, without a taste of first kiss, without togetherness? With only a whisper of romantic poetry in the air to keep the passion burning, or with time, distance, and vile circumstance separating lovers at every turn? How does one call love two hearts finally meeting as one, but only in their graves? Layla and Majnun embody this kind of love: innocent, tragic, and anguished, yet rare, pure, and everlasting. <br/><br/>Persian poet Niẓāmi Ganjavi (1141-1209) gave </span>
  <span id="freeText3413163298874159521" style="display:none">How can love endure without a touch of one’s hand, without a taste of first kiss, without togetherness? With only a whisper of romantic poetry in the air to keep the passion burning, or with time, distance, and vile circumstance separating lovers at every turn? How does one call love two hearts finally meeting as one, but only in their graves? Layla and Majnun embody this kind of love: innocent, tragic, and anguished, yet rare, pure, and everlasting. <br /><br />Persian poet Niẓāmi Ganjavi (1141-1209) gave this tale of one of the greatest star-crossed lovers in the literary world a timeless rendition. Commissioned by ruler Shirvanshah to compose a poem about the legendary romance of the love-mad poet Qays ibn Al-Mulawwah and his ladylove Layla, Niẓāmi added a Persian touch to the original Arabic story, and also drew inspiration from Udhrite love poetry or “poems of lost love in the desert”, which views love as chaste, unrequited, and unfulfilled.<br /><br />Interestingly, Niẓāmi was initially reluctant to do the poem, thinking the subject too simple and ill-suited for his refined audience at the royal court. But his son urged him on, telling him, "wherever tales of love are read, this will add spice to them". True enough, Niẓāmi’s poem enjoyed a popular following, widely imitated over time and even translated into many languages. It could’ve been such a waste had Niẓāmi ended up ditching the project/commission as he had first intended to do—we wouldn’t have the chance to read this lyrical tale of love that goes beyond the conventional. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3413163298874159521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

