    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1942309228" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1942309228" />
    <a title="Mina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1843780-mina"><img alt="Mina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610189535p2/1843780.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1942309228?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mina" href="/user/show/1843780-mina">Mina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/700479.The_Story_of_Layla_and_Majnun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1843780-mina?shelf=asian">asian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1843780-mina?shelf=love">love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1843780-mina?shelf=dnf">dnf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1942309228" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16442445162630188209">I reached page 19.<br/><br/>Love is a delicate, complicated subject across cultures.<br/><br/>However here, the whole of society is &quot;ashamed&quot; when it happens - constantly, predictably ashamed, acting as if it were an incurable madness and they had no kindness for the mad. Love is madness, perseverence is madness.<br/><br/>More importantly, Quays&apos; father watched him (the eponymous Manjun is named Quays) follow Layla&apos;s tribe on foot for what is apparently a long period of time, hoping it will wear off. There is no quarrel betw</span>
  <span id="freeText16442445162630188209" style="display:none">I reached page 19.<br /><br />Love is a delicate, complicated subject across cultures.<br /><br />However here, the whole of society is "ashamed" when it happens - constantly, predictably ashamed, acting as if it were an incurable madness and they had no kindness for the mad. Love is madness, perseverence is madness.<br /><br />More importantly, Quays' father watched him (the eponymous Manjun is named Quays) follow Layla's tribe on foot for what is apparently a long period of time, hoping it will wear off. There is no quarrel between the tribes, no reason not to wed them, except apparently that romantic heterosexual love is shameful. Only then, when it becomes clear the infatuation won't pass, ashamed and desperate, the father decides to go woo Layla's tribe to get Layla for his son.<br /><br />He's a bit of a heavy-handed businessman, but Layla's father is however admirably level-headed and tells him, not unkindly, "I know of you: You're rich, powerful and renowned as a worthy tribe leader and despite your sharp words, it's an attractive offer, but your son is wrong in the head. Get your son healed of this madness (still love), and then maybe we can talk marriage" <br /><br />Hence I, foreign reader, infer: <br /><br />1) the translation is at fault. Unlikely. Actions and paraphrasing of the driest sort repetitively yield the same theme. Also mind, that the title is "Layla and the Madman", not "Layla and Quays" like we would have, say, "Romeo and Julieta", "Tristan and Isolde"<br /><br />2) Love is an undesirable unsightly all-consuming madness. Literally. Look, the lad keeps crying and moaning and forgets to eat. I half expected Layla's father to say, "look, what if after they marry the next thing he'll do is shag a goat in public?"<br /><br />3) There is little to no character definition or development so the then-Persian culture and the contemporary cultures it yielded didn't sincerely believe there is anything worth writing about as far as love and the human character are concerned. In which case the only thing of worth about this intensely plot-driven story about a couple of separated lovers is the poetry, sadly lost in translation. <br /><br />That being said, Nizami translations are rare as fuck in the West.<br /><br />4) This culture is inflexible. The only character it cares for is respecting the letter of law - which law that is, I know not, since the poem is pre-Islam, from what I understand. No thinking on their feet, purely reactive.<br /><br />And that's where I DNF. Layla's father's answer is admirably clear, succinct and well-argumented. He does not refuse out of spite. He refuses because the culture says Quays is beyond help. And you can write a story about that, but this result of a translation is remarkably heavy-handed and repetitive.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16442445162630188209" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

